problem: What is the units digit of the product of all the odd positive integers between 10 and 110?
solution: Any odd multiple of 5 will end in a units digit of 5 (even multiples will end in a units digit of 0). Since all the integers we are multiplying are odd and some of them have a factor of 5, the product will be an odd multiple of 5 with a units digit of $\boxed{5}$.
socratic_questions:
1. What is the range of positive odd integers between 10 and 110?
2. How can we determine the units digit of a product involving odd integers?
3. What is the units digit of the product of any odd integer with the digit 5?
4. Can you explain why odd multiples of 5 will always have a units digit of 5?
5. How can we determine if a product will have an odd or even units digit?
6. Are there any other patterns or concepts related to units digits that can help us solve this problem?
